{
  "doc_id": "33276",
  "text": "DG is a discrete structure that is postnatally developed [CITATION_1] . After birth, the first granule neurons are formed in the hippocampal neuroepithelium and move to form a DG primordium. Afterward, granule precursor cells, also from this area, migrate to the primordium. These mitotic cells form a germinal matrix that gives rise to an adult DG after 1 month of life [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . After finishing the formation, some neural precursor cells remain in the SGZ dividing and constantly generating newborn granule neurons [CITATION_4] , which connect with the preexistent trisynaptic circuit of the hippocampus [CITATION_5] . Newborn granule neurons have a major role in hippocampus-dependent memory and learning tasks and in anxiety and depression [CITATION_6] .",
